<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I"><UNDER>STATEMENT OF CLAIM</UNDER></TI>
<P>1. Daniel Forsyth is a resident of the Halifax Regional Municipality.</P>
<P>2. The defendant, Halifax Regional Municipality, is a body corporate and a municipality in the Province of Nova Scotia, and is and was at all material times hereto responsible for and had control over the construction, maintenance, upkeep, and safety of sidewalks located within the Halifax Regional Municipality, including responsibility for and oversight of street signs, parking signs, and/or bus signs located on the sidewalks.</P>
<P>3. The plaintiff states that on April 14, 2015, he had been visiting his father in the Veterans Memorial Hospital in the Halifax Regional Municipality. At the time of his visit, for certain medical reasons, the plaintiff was using a wheelchair.</P>
<P>4. The plaintiff states that following the conclusion of his visit, he exited the Veterans Memorial Hospital and entered onto a street known as Veterans Memorial Lane located immediately adjacent to the Hospital building.</P>
<P>5. The plaintiff states that upon exiting the building, he made his way to the sidewalk on the south side of Veterans Memorial Lane. He then began to proceed in an easterly direction on Veterans Memorial Lane, moving towards the intersection of Veterans Memorial Lane and Summer Street.</P>
<P>6. The plaintiff states that on April 14, 2015, there was snow on the ground but it was not snowing that day. There was an accumulation of snow on the sidewalk on which the plaintiff was travelling. The accumulation was such that there were banks of snow on each edge of the sidewalk, creating a limited lane of travel for the plaintiff in his wheelchair.</P>
<P>7. The plaintiff states that his wheelchair is powered by a motor. As the plaintiff was operating his wheelchair along Veterans Memorial Lane, it struck an object causing the wheelchair to tip and throwing the plaintiff from the wheelchair.</P>
<P>8. The plaintiff states that the object which he struck was the remains of a traffic or bus sign which had been broken or otherwise sawed off. The remains of the post extended between 3&ndash;6 inches from the sidewalk. The post was not visible at the time due to the snow accumulation.</P>
<P>9. The plaintiff states that there were no signs or indicators as to the presence of the broken post protruding from the sidewalk.</P>
<P>10. The plaintiff relies upon the applicable provisions of the <EM>Municipal Government Act</EM>, S.N.S. 1998, c.18.</P>
<P>11. As a result of the accident described above, the plaintiff sustained bodily injuries and damages.</P>
<P>12. The plaintiff states that the accident and resulting injuries were caused by the negligence of the defendant, it's employees or agents. Particulars of the negligence include:
<P1>a) Failure to maintain the sidewalk in a safe and prudent manner;</P1>
<P1>b) Allowing the remains of the traffic pole to stay in the sidewalk when the defendant, its employees or agents knew or ought to have known the presence of the partial pole posed a danger to the users of the sidewalk;</P1>
<P1>c) Failure to adhere to applicable policies regarding the maintenance and safety of the sidewalk;</P1>
<P1>d) failure to place any or adequate warnings or cautions to users of the sidewalk regarding the presence of the remains of the pole, when the defendant, it's employees or agents knew or ought to have known that the pole presented a potential danger to users of the sidewalk; and</P1>
<P1>e) such other negligence as may appear.</P1></P>
<P>12. The plaintiff repeats the foregoing and claims against the defendant for the following:
<P1>a) General damages;</P1>
<P1>b) Special Damages, particulars of which will be delivered at or before at trial;</P1>
<P1>c) Loss of Housekeeping Capacity;</P1>
<P1>d) Costs;</P1>
<P1>e) Pre-judgement Interest; and</P1>
<P1>f) Such other damages as this honourable court deems fit to award.</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>DATED</BOLD> at Dartmouth, in the Halifax Regional Municipality, this 5<SUP>th</SUP> day of October, 2015.</P>
