<BLOCK2><TI>MOTION</TI>
<P>I represent the Defendant Halifax Regional Municipality (HRM) in this matter. The Plaintiff Daniel Forsyth seeks a pre-trial ruling on the following:
<P1>(a) When Desmond Munden gave discovery evidence on October 27, 2016, did he do so as the designated manager of the Defendant; and</P1>
<P1>(b) The extent to which the discovery evidence given by Desmond Munden is binding on the Defendant at trial. The Plaintiff brings this motion pursuant to Rules 12, 14.14, 18.02 and 18.20.</P1></P>
<P>If Mr. Munden testified as a designated manager his discovery evidence can be used at trial for all purposes under Rule 18.20(2). If he testified as an employee then Rule 18.20(3) applies.</P>
<P>HRM submits that in the circumstances of this case there is no basis to conclude that Mr. Munden was a &ldquo;designated manager&rdquo; under Rule 14.14 or Rule 18.20(2). HRM further submits that part (b) of the Plaintiff's motion involves evidentiary findings and is outside the ambit of Rule 12.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>LAW AND ARGUMENT</TI>
<P>There is no disagreement regarding the exchange of communications between the Counsel leading up to the discovery of Mr. Munden. Mr. Rumscheidt in correspondence dated November 17, 2015, was clear that he wanted to <BOLD>&ldquo;discover a representative of HRM. To the extent possible, please forward a representative who can address the general policies of HRM regarding sidewalk maintenance and signage as well as the background or history with respect to the removal of any signage on the street in question&rdquo;.</BOLD> A copy of Mr. Rumscheidt's correspondence is attached to the Affidavit of Joel Plater as Exhibit B.</P>
<P>Via e-mail dated August 30, 2016 (Exhibit C of Joel Plater's Affidavit), Mr. Rumscheidt was advised that HRM's witness would be Desmond Munden, Works Supervisor with Traffic Management Transportation and Public Works.</P>
<P>At no time prior to the discovery did the Plaintiff indicate that he was seeking to discover a &ldquo;designated manager&rdquo; under Rule 14.14 or 18.20(2). The Plaintiff simply stated that he was seeking to discover a representative of HRM for the purposes set out in the November 17, 2015, correspondence. At no time did the Defendant indicate that it was advancing a designated manager under Rule 14.14 or Rule 18.20(2).</P>
<P>Rule 14.14 often has little bearing on litigation involving the Municipality. Witnesses are put forward as employees unless a specific request is made for the discovery of a designated manager. Most litigation against the Municipality involves claims for personal injury. These sorts of claims very seldom lend themselves to the need to discover a designated manager. For example, in a case involving a motor vehicle accident the driver of the HRM vehicle would be discovered as a fact witness, as would a police officer involved in a case claiming excessive use of force or wrongful arrest. Employee witnesses can speak directly to the facts within their knowledge and matters within the scope of their employment duties.</P>
<P>In this case, Mr. Munden was the HRM employee who was responsible for service requests relating to fixing/repairing road signage within the Municipality. Mr. Munden describes his job duties at pages 7 and 8 of the discovery transcript. As a Works Supervisor, Mr. Munden was the employee who could best address the general policies of HRM regarding signage as well as the background or history with respect to the removal of any signage on the street in question. He was produced in response to the specific request made by the Plaintiff, not as a designated manager under Rule 14.14 or Rule 18.20(2).</P>
<P>Mr. Munden testified at discovery that his duties as a Works Supervisor involved managing services requests for fixing/repairing road signage. The witness was not asked if he had authority as a Works Supervisor to bind HRM with his subjective opinions or personal views, or if he was authorized to speak to matters outside of his job description. It is doubtful that Mr. Munden even understood what a designated manager was.</P>
<P>HRM submits that the exchange between Mr. Rumscheidt and Mr. Harfouche at the commencement of the discovery is not determinative of the matter. Neither party referred to Mr. Munden as the designated manager. The brief exchange between Counsel cannot be viewed in a vacuum without reference to the correspondence which set out the parameters for the discovery. There is no direct evidence from the witness that he was a designated manager of the Defendant; to the contrary, the witness was clear as to what his job duties entailed.</P>
<BLOCK3><TI>Rule 12</TI>
<P>Rule 12 authorizes a determination of only an issue of law. Under Rule 12.01(1) a party may in <BOLD>limited circumstances</BOLD>, seek the determination of a question of law before the rest of the issues in a proceeding are determined, even though the parties disagree about facts relevant to the question.</P>
<P>Rule 12.02 sets out in what limited circumstances the court may separate a question of law from other issues in a proceeding and provide for its determination before the trial. Under the Rule, a judge may only do so if all of the following apply:
<P1>(a) The facts necessary to determine the question can be found without the trial or hearing;</P1>
<P1>(b) The determination will reduce the length of the proceeding, duration of the trial or hearing, or expense of the proceeding;</P1>
<P1>(c) No facts to be found in order to answer the question will remain in issue after the determination.</P1></P>
<P>In <CASEREF><SOC>Mahoney v. Cumis Life Insurance Co.</SOC><CITE>2011 NSCA 31</CITE></CASEREF> (Tab # 1) the ambit of the Rule 12 was discussed by Justice Fichaud at paragraphs 18, 19, 20, and 21 as follows:
<QUOTE><P>18 So the first step with Rule 12 is to identify the pure legal question to be determined. Rule 12.01(1) permits a motion for determination of &ldquo;a question of law&rdquo;. Rule 12.03(1) permits the judge either to determine &ldquo;the question of law&rdquo; or appoint a time to determine that question of law. The Rule does not authorize a determination of a question of fact or mixed fact and law, excepting only those facts that scaffold the point of pure law under Rule 12.02(a) as I have discussed.</P>
<P>19 The second step is to identify all the facts that are necessary to determine that question of pure law. Nothing in Rule 12 permits a judge to decide facts that are unnecessary to determine the question of pure law in the motion. A party who wishes an assessment of evidence on other matters, leading to a judgment by interlocutory ruling, should make or join a summary judgment motion under Rule 13.04 (&ldquo;Summary judgment on evidence&rdquo;).</P>
<P>20 The third step under Rule 12 is to decide whether all those facts necessary to determine the issue of pure law in the motion &ldquo;can be found without the trial or hearing&rdquo;.</P>
<P>21 This third step generates the question&mdash;What does Rule 12.02(a) mean that those facts &ldquo;can be found without the trial or hearing&rdquo;? In my view, it does not mean that a judge under Rule 12 can assess evidence in the same fashion as in a motion for summary judgment on the evidence under Rule 13.04. Under Rule 13.04, a responding party must &ldquo;put his best foot forward&rdquo; with evidence or risk a determination that there is no genuine issue of material fact requiring trial, or that its claim or defence has no real chance of success, and a consequent dismissal of the action or defence: <CASEREF><SOC>Aylward v. Dalhousie University</SOC><CITE>2011 NSCA 20</CITE><PARANUM>11</PARANUM></CASEREF>, affirming <CASEREF><SOC>Dalhousie University v. Aylward</SOC><CITE>2010 NSSC 65</CITE><PARANUM>20&ndash;25</PARANUM></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>Ristow v. National Bank Financial Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2010 NSCA 79</CITE><PARANUM>5&ndash;9</PARANUM></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>Nova Scotia (Attorney General) v. Brill</SOC><CITE>2010 NSCA 69</CITE><PARANUM>173</PARANUM></CASEREF>. Rule 12 does not give the chambers judge that power. A judge under Rule 12 <BOLD>may not determine contested facts</BOLD> that might hinge on testimony at a trial. That is the point of Rule 12.02(a)'s condition that &ldquo;the facts ... can be found without the trial&rdquo;. [emphasis added]</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>On the first step, HRM submits that whether Rule 18.20(2) or 18.20(3) applies is a pure &ldquo;question of law&rdquo;.</P>
<P>On the second step, whether or not Mr. Munden was the designated manager of the Defendant at the time of his discovery requires a finding of fact. HRM submits that the facts that are necessary to determine the question of law in this case are as follows:
<P1>1. Did the Defendant provide formal notification under Rule 14.14 that Desmond Munden was its designated manager?</P1>
<P1>2. Prior to discovery, did the Plaintiff make a request to discover the designated manager of the Defendant?</P1>
<P1>3. Prior to discovery did the Defendant communicate to the Plaintiff that Mr. Munden was being advanced for discovery as the designated manager of the Defendant?</P1>
<P1>4. At discovery, did Mr. Munden testify that he was the designated manager of the Defendant?</P1>
<P1>5. Was Mr. Munden asked any questions regarding the scope of his authority to bind the Defendant?</P1>
<P1>6. What were Mr. Munden's job duties?</P1></P>
<P>On the third step, HRM submits that the facts necessary to determine the issue of pure law in the motion can be found without the trial or hearing. The essential facts necessary to make a determination as to whether Mr. Munden was the designated manager of HRM do not appear to be in dispute. The Plaintiff agrees that no designated manager was identified under Rule 14.14 and that he did not make a request to discovery a designated manager. At no time did the Defendant indicate that Mr. Munden was its designated manager. Mr. Munden did not testify at discovery that he was a designated manager, nor was he asked any questions about his authority to bind HRM. The exchange between Counsel prior to discovery did not make any reference to a designated manager. Mr. Munden described his job duties which involved managing service requests for fixing/repairing road signage. It does not appear that any of the above facts are in dispute.</P>
<P>I note that our Court has dealt with a similar issue on a pre-trial motion. For example, the purpose to which discovery evidence could be used at trial was the subject of an application in <CASEREF><SOC>Nova Scotia (Attorney General) v. Royal &amp; Sun Alliance Insurance Co. of Canada</SOC><CITE>[2005] NSJ No. 223</CITE></CASEREF> (Tab # 2). In that case, the Court needed to decide whether the Minister of Justice was an officer, director or manager of a party that is a corporation such that his discovery evidence could be used under Rule 18.14(1)(b) [new Rule 18.20(2)] for all purposes. Justice Moir dealt with the matter on a Rule 25 motion [new Rule 12] as he found that the assessment of the application engaged evidence that was &ldquo;so uncontentious that all material facts necessary to answer the question could be determined easily without a trial&rdquo;. In that case, the Minister of Justice was found to be an officer of the Crown.</P>
<P>The Plaintiff in correspondence dated November 17, 2015, made a request for a specific witness. The witness who best fulfilled the Plaintiff's requirements was produced for discovery. Mr. Munden described his job duties with the Municipality. His description of his role with the Municipality could in no way lead to the conclusion that he was the designated manager of the Defendant.</P>
<P>Mr. Harfouche attended at the discovery on behalf of the Defendant. He was not solicitor of record. Prior to the commencement of the discovery Mr. Harfouche confirmed that Mr. Munden was a representative of the Defendant and that his answers would bind the municipality. Rule 18.20(3) sets a limit on the use of a discovery transcript where a deponent is an employee. Under the Rule, Mr. Munden's is only able to bind the municipality with respect to matters within the scope his authority. In HRM's view the exchange between Mr. Rumscheidt and Mr. Harfouche at the commencement of the discovery did not elevate Mr. Munden from an employee in charge of managing service requests for fixing/repairing road signage to that of a designated manager.</P>
<P>HRM respectfully submits that in the circumstances of this case, Rule 18.02(3) is applicable in that evidence given by an officer or employee of a corporate party who is not a designated manager may be used for any purpose by an adverse party, except answers outside the witnesses' scope of authority are not admissions by the corporate party.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI>Findings of Fact Outside the Ambit of Rule 12</TI>
<P>HRM submits that the only question that can be answered on this motion is which Rule applies to Mr. Munden's discovery evidence. Part (b) of the Plaintiff's motion cannot properly be dealt with under Rule 12 as the facts necessary to determine the question cannot be found without the trial. Whether something Mr. Munden said at discovery was an admission, or admissible under the rules of evidence or within his authority (where Rule 18.20(3) applies) is a matter for the trial judge. Furthermore, the admission of discovery evidence at trial is subject to relevancy, weight and questions of admissibility.</P>
<P>Mr. Dunn, who authored the e-mail put to Mr. Munden, will be required to testify about his investigations and the basis for his &ldquo;presumptions&rdquo;. Determinations will be required to be made regarding the admissibility of the presumptions contained in the e-mail and whether those presumptions were accepted as conclusions by HRM or simply remained as the personal presumptions and opinions of the author of the e-mail. The extent of Mr. Munden's authority relating to the acceptance of presumptions on behalf his employer will likewise be in issue.</P>
<P>There will be no reduction in the length of the trial or hearing as it is highly likely that both Mr. Munden and Mr. Dunn will be required for trial. Facts will still remain in issue, such as the scope of Mr. Munden's authority and the qualifications of both Mr. Dunn and Mr. Munden to provide opinion evidence on sign post markings.</P>
<P>As set out in his brief, the Plaintiff is seeking a ruling that several admissions which he says were made by Mr. Munden on discovery are binding on HRM at trial.</P>
<BLOCK4><N>1.</N><TI>The location of the remnants of which post Mr. Forsyth struck with his wheel chair.</TI>
<P>The Plaintiff says that his claim relates to the sign post that is located closest to the intersection of Veteran's Memorial Way with Summer Street. No one from HRM witnessed the Plaintiff's mishap. The Plaintiff's evidence regarding the location and the reason for his fall is just that: the Plaintiff's evidence. Whether or not the Plaintiff struck the remnants of the post at this location is a finding for the trial judge.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>2.</N><TI>That the post in question had been knocked over as a result of snow plowing work.</TI>
<P>This HRM submits is the main reason for this motion in that the Plaintiff is seeking to bind HRM to what he says is an admission that the post was struck and knocked down by an HRM snow plow.</P>
<P>At page 28 of the discovery transcript Mr. Rumscheidt posed the following question to Mr. Munden while directing him to Matthew Dunn's e-mail of May 5, 2016:
<QUOTE><P>Q. Right. And again, read this if you need to but my&mdash;I take it the conclusion, or the assumption that HRM came to was that Post No. 1, that's what Mr. Dunn calls it&mdash;the closest to Summer Street that was involved in Mr. Forsyth's accident&mdash;that in all likelihood that the post had been knocked over or broken as a result of snow plowing efforts. Is that what&mdash;the conclusion HRM reached.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>Nowhere in Mr. Dunn's e-mail does he suggest that in all likelihood the post had been knocked over or broken as a result of snow plowing efforts. He simply says that &ldquo;one would presume it had been knocked over by snow clearing vehicles&rdquo;. Mr. Rumscheidt also incorrectly suggests to Mr. Munden that Mr. Dunn's &ldquo;conclusion, or assumption&rdquo; was the conclusion or assumption of HRM.</P>
<P>Even though Mr. Dunn is clear in his e-mail that he is simply &ldquo;presuming&rdquo; Mr. Rumscheidt goes on to suggest to the witness that the conclusion HRM has come to is that the sign got knocked over by snow plowing efforts. Mr. Munden simply agrees with Mr. Rumscheidt. Regardless, whether Mr. Munden agrees with Mr. Rumscheidt's interpretation of Mr. Dunn's e-mail, the email speaks for itself&mdash;Mr. Dunn made an assumption. He did not draw any definitive conclusions about how the sign post was knocked down nor would he have the qualifications to do so.</P>
<P>HRM witnesses will testify at trial that posts become detached in all seasons for assorted reasons including storm damage, rust, and impact with vehicles. The only way HRM would have a clear understanding of how a post came to be knocked down is if someone included that information in a report. For example, a police officer or a citizen may have direct knowledge of a post having been knocked down by an MVA. The main concern of HRM is the repair of damaged signs, not forensic investigation into the cause of the failure.</P>
<P>Later during the discovery at page 32 Mr. Rumscheidt asks Mr. Munden whether he agrees that the photos attached to Mr. Dunn's e-mail show snow removal damage along the side of post 1. Mr. Munden's response is &ldquo;yes, correct&rdquo;. At this point, however, Mr. Rumscheidt had already incorrectly suggested to Mr. Munden that Mr. Dunn was speaking on behalf of HRM and that HRM had concluded that the sign got knocked over by snow plowing efforts. This, is simply an incorrect interpretation of Mr. Dunn's e-mail which was the focus of all the questions put to Mr. Munden relating to the markings on the post.</P>
<P>Neither Mr. Munden at discovery, or Mr. Dunn in his e-mail, made any reference to the post having been knocked down by an HRM employee or an HRM snow plow. The post has been in its current position since at least 1991. It would not be possible to tell from a visual inspection of the post or an inspection of a photograph of the post (which Mr. Munden was asked to do on discovery) to make any determination as to when any of the marks on the post were made let alone whether the marks were made by an HRM plow driven by an HRM employee in 2014/2015.</P>
<P>Neither Mr. Munden or Mr. Dunn have sufficient personal knowledge to answer the question regarding the marks on the post. The testimony regarding the markings of the post is inadmissible opinion. Opinion evidence of this sort would require scientific or technical expertise whereas Mr. Dunn was merely speculating and Mr. Munden merely agreeing with Mr. Dunn's inadmissible speculations. Furthermore, in HRM's view, the questions put to Mr. Munden misstated or misrepresented the contents of Mr. Dunn's e-mail and as such, the responses are of little or value to the determination of the issues at trial.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>3.</N><TI>That the post was knocked over at some point in time between August 2014 and the April 16, 2015 accident.</TI>
<P>Based on historical data from Google Earth, it appears that the post which was closest to Veteran's Memorial Way was severed from its base sometime between August 2014, and April 16, 2015. HRM cannot speak to the accuracy of the Google Map data. HRM had no knowledge of the downed post prior to the Plaintiff's fall.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>4.</N><TI>That the post was repaired at some point between Mr. Forsyth's accident and October 23, 2015.</TI>
<P>HRM employees will testify at trial about repairs to posts along Veteran's Memorial Way. A photograph taken on October 23, 2015, shows the post back in its proper location. What posts were repaired and when the repairs were made are findings of facts for the trial judge.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>AFTER DISCOVERY</TI>
<P>HRM also points out that following discovery, it made it clear to the Plaintiff that it would not be relying on the presumptions of Matthew Dunn or the opinions of Desmond Munden (which were based on the presumptions contained in Mr. Dunn's email) at trial. The failure of Mr. Harfouche to object to the line of questioning calling for opinions from Mr. Munden or those which misinterpreted Mr. Dunn's e-mail is not determinative of the matter as oversights are often covered by counsel after discovery.</P>
<P>HRM has been cooperative with the Plaintiff regarding further discoveries. A request is currently on hold for the discovery of a second witness who can speak to policies regarding snow removal damage relating to sign posts. HRM was unaware that the Plaintiff was claiming that Mr. Munden was the designated manager of HRM until the filing of the within motion.</P>
<P>HRM asks this court to dismiss the Plaintiff's motion with costs.</P>
<P>All of which is respectfully submitted.</P>
